review_text: Very historical, very great, has a very entaining osprey!
Just check it out and enjoy nature's gifts!

Loved it. Great shape, greens rolled smoothly , tee boxes were excellent. Not a terribly difficult course. Would definitely go back. Bar/snack stand at the turn was not opened yet, so hopefully next time that glizzy at the turn will make this course even better.

Had a three Hour NINE holes today.  Finished nine holes and went into the "pro shop" and asked for a rain check because is was getting dark and it was just too busy.    Attendant so NO,  you booked. Twilight round, there are no rain checks.    Tee time booked was 2.12 pm on a Sunday, sunset is around 8 pm.   Teed off at 2.35pm and was on the first tee 30 minutes early.  IMO maybe not a good plan to retain local business.
Great course, enjoyed the layout and the price point was the icing on the cake. The front and the back play like two different courses, which was fun.

I've wanted to play Acushnet River Valley for many years and finally got a chance to play last week.  The wait was very well worth it.  Great layout, awesome design of the various holes but the course condition put it over the top for me.  Everything was in fantastic shape, but want I loved was the firm fairways, so easy to compress the ball off the turf.  They have a nice driving range and practice green as well.

Acushnet River Valley is one of the best values anywhere. $39 everyday after 1 p.m. for 18 holes and cart. That's almost unheard of. At that price point you wouldn't expect much, but the course is in really good shape. The greens are awesome and the layout makes it a fun round. Some real memorable holes and shots here. The only issue - after 1 p.m. it's a total free-for-all on the first tee. If you come at the wrong time, it could be a 5-6 hour round.

** I originally gave 4 stars but had to edit my review to 2 stars. We had a tee time for 3:50 pm, we get to the tee 10 minutes early and there are 5 groups waiting to go out (this happens frequently). We don't tee off until 4:30 pm. We play at a normal pace, keeping up with the group in front of us. We get to the 18th tee around 8:30 pm, it's getting dark. The ranger comes out to tell us that we need to pick up the pace because they closed at 8 pm and are waiting for us to finish. Well, we would have finished by 8 pm if we didn't waste 40 minutes sitting on the first tee.

Acushnet River needs to space out their tee times to have a reasonable pace of play. The course is nice and a great value, but the slow play leaves you frustrated.

Hello good morning golfed acushnet  Valley golf course yesterday  10-29 -23.The course itself is amazing, especially the back nine which is a link style. I will definitely be going back to this course more than once a year. The price, for the round was perfect for the condition of it the only thing about it that I thought they could improve on is  to have the potholes on the cart path filled in  in certain spots.  One  more little thing that I liked a lot when I was in the parking lot getting my stuff together a young gentleman came up to me and gave me an electric cart which I thought was pretty cool.  Again highly recommend this course .

The course is in excellent condition throughout. The greens roll true and have good consistent speed. The layout and variety of holes keeps things interesting. The pace of play was on the slower side, even with limited play due to rainy conditions.

8/18/23 - played the course again as part of the scramble fundraiser.  The course is in amazing condition.  A downpour moved through, which suspended play for about an hour.  The course has great drainage, which made the course very playable for the final 10 holes.

I love this course, the front/back play different, and the course is always in good shape. My only gripe is the poor customer service. Double booking, get ready to wait and tee off late. Between the old mustache starter man who is quick to yell at customers for no reason at all. The pro shop or director of golf don't return phone calls. Like I said, I love this place but when I recommend it to another person, I make sure to mention its downfalls.

Nice walking paths and rivers/streams. There are elevation changes and roots, rocks and sticks on the path so bring proper shoes, water and a camera for the nice scenery.

Beautiful views and wildlife is abundant. Very little trash and well maintained.
Great place to take the whole family for a nice walk. I love to take my dog here. They have a large parking lot too.
It's a small place, but my dog and I like popping in there for a quick walk when we're out running errands.
1st time here. Such a beautiful place. Came with family for a nice small walk on a really nice 1/2mile  loop trail.
A wonderful place to walk through and relax. Also a great place to take pictures, especially if you have a great DSLR camera!
Such a nice relaxing place to go for a little hike. We'll be going back in the spring to see the eels and fish swim upstream.
Excellent easy walking loop.  Some small hills, platform by the water to breathe and some rocks that act like benches for a rest.  Trail was clear to follow.

The sawmill and the rivers end in New Bedford are some of the great revitalizing the city is doing. Sometimes they do get it right.
Beautiful places
Had to go into woods alittle but great fishing spot, perch, sunfish, bass, catfish too!!
If you're hunting, this is the spot to go to.  deer Definitely walk through there
A nice little walk through the woods with good scenes.  Pond is super close, just be careful not to walk into people's backyards they're very close!
Place is fantastic for tick watching and bees.
Great service, flight of Marguerita's were so good, all our seafood dishes were excellent.
Great fishing!! Use live bait though.
It is not an easy palace to visit, but needed projection.  Thank you DCR.
A gr8 spot 4 nature walks, fishing, hunting and kayaking
A gem of the city. Perfect place to take the kids.

An excellent site to explore and take pictures of; perfect for nature lovers and photographers alike. The historical significance of this location gives it even more beauty than it would have otherwise. I, personally, enjoy the ruin-like condition it's in, it helps preserve what it was and show how nature takes back what was previously its to begin with. Definitely gave me plenty of inspiration.
Such a beautiful spot for weddings, maternity photos, family photos and more!!!! Love how my photos came out and as a photographer is my go to !!!
I just drove all the way here and the road is blocked off and it looks like they are demolishing it. I'm glad it said OPEN on this listing
Great place for photographs for events , would definitely be a nice spot to picnic.
Very cool piece of history, but the state of the structure is somewhat concerning. Basically in ruins.
Nice place to pull over and take a pic

This place was creepy..when we got out if our car and started exploring after about 5 minutes we heard coyotes howling from every direction,the sound was getting ckoser and closer,as soon as we got back in our car the howling stopped. We went at night on full moon, would love to explore during day.
It's always a nice little stop to do. Some general clean up of the land could be done as well as the sign which is half missing. Overall a nice little spot to hang out for a bit.

This place looks like the place to be come summer, with a generous splash pad, a dozen or so picnic tables and grills, a wide field, and tons of hiking trails.

I will say though...hunting?!?!  I am not anti-hunting, but it would be nice to know it wasn't a possibility year-round at a state park.  It literally says to wear bright colors so you don't get shot!

Other than THAT, which I have no insider knowledge of how prevalent it is or not, I really enjoyed my trip.

I especially liked that all dogs I saw were leashed, which is a rule at DCR parks, but not always enforced or followed.  Thank you!!!!

And there are bathrooms open, but they closed well before the park did.

Cool history and very accessible.  Even the trails aren't super bumpy.
I came here looking for pukwudgie and any other Bridgewater Triangle spooks and goblins. I heard some strange noises, but did not see any tiny humanoids. Still a great walk through the forest though!
I have been coming here since I was a kid, when you had the pool. I find it very peaceful and great for the kids and pets.

Great place to take children of all ages! Amazing hiking/walking trails. If you like the nature and everything that comes with it you'll love the trails. Also has a wading pool for children and parents. They also have sites where you can set up for the day with charcoal grills. Bathrooms on site.
They allow hunting here so just be careful.  Beautiful place for hiking.

Pretty good hike! There's definite evidence of extracurricular activities in the forest, but don't let that stop you from climbing to the top of profile rock or exploring the trails. Tons of evergreen trees. Pictures are of the view from the top of the rock. Be careful as private property does border the forest in several locations

Nice place to hike in the summer, fall, winter, and spring dont get lost however use maps if needed, I was able to still get celluar service on cell phone throughout the trails. You would also see motorcross bike trails as well, and occasional wildlife. Great place to barbecue with picnic benches and if you have kids it have a nice waddling pool for small children.

Update,
Folks I drive a Acura rsx. A little sports coupe. I drove through every single trail this park had to offer. It's all totally accessible, and the pot holes are a test of your skills and mettle as a driver. the peace of mind is unreal and you see absolutely no one. Let alone its a major part of the "bridge water triangle" get in here folks and live !

Update: In 2024 the Coalition began a project to restore the bogs. It's going to take a while, but I'm excited to see how they transform this place. I moved my review to 3 stars, because unfortunately I feel like a lot of mature growth was destroyed, including some very old trees. Regardless of the restoration, the Bog photos you see in my photos are no longer relevant. Going to be at least 10+ years before it looks like that again.

An amazing spot for a nice walk or run. Very well kept and beautiful. My only cautionary note is be careful here: it's a great spot for dog walking. While I love dogs, I've caught a few unleashed dogs by surprise on my runs and had some close calls. Some folks let their dogs run free and not all of them are friendly.
Great place to relax and enjoy nature. There are trails in the woods and open paths at the bogs. Never crowded (but usually a lot of dogs) and very peaceful no matter the weather

This is a great place to bike!
Along the boundaries of the former cranberry bogs and Some wooded paths. Many turtles,  dragonflies, birds,  and butterflies! No marked trails, but a map is readily available online.
Be aware The paths are dirt and grass.
mountain bike tires are more suitable for this trail.
This place is great if you want a nice walk in some nature and if you go into the woods there are a lot of tasks back there and it's a really good place to clear your head
Beautiful little path through formerly cranberry bogs. Lots of butterflies, birds and red ear slider turtles.
Lovely spot to walk, joins up with Tripps Mill. Two wonderful preserves from the Buzzards Bay Coalition, thanks guys!
Lovely place to walk, take pictures and just relax.
Open fields, clean,smooth dirt paths, good for walking, biking or running
A great place to go for interaction with nature in the middle of the city! An approximately 1 mile walk that is meditative for me!
Great place to take a walk
Qwery
Peaceful
